            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Sharma\u2019s life story is woven into the fabric of San Francisco\u2019s Inner Richmond district, smelling faintly of steam and clean linen. He was born to an immigrant father from Pune, India, who arrived in the 1970s with boundless ambition, and a second-generation Irish-American mother from the Sunset District. His father, Raj, opened \"Sharma & Son's Cleaners\" on Clement Street, a testament to his belief in the American dream. David grew up in the apartment above the shop, a childhood defined by the rhythmic hiss of the presses and the diverse stories of his neighbors who brought in their Sunday best.\n\nInitially, David wanted nothing to do with the family business. He saw it as his father's world, not his. He enrolled at San Francisco State University, earning a Bachelor's in Business Administration with dreams of a corporate career in the Financial District, a world away from the manual labor he\u2019d known. However, a turning point came during his senior year when his father suffered a major health crisis. Faced with the prospect of his parents losing their livelihood, David put his downtown ambitions aside and took over managing the shop. What began as a temporary duty slowly became his destiny.\n\nNow 50, David is a fixture of the neighborhood. The \"and Son's\" was dropped from the sign a decade ago after his divorce, a quiet acknowledgment that the lineage would likely end with him. His life is one of disciplined routine. He wakes at 6 a.m., walks the half-mile to his shop, and spends his day greeting customers by name, many of whom he\u2019s known for over 30 years. He is the keeper of their garments and, in a way, their histories. His social life unfolds over the counter and at the local cafes where he grabs his lunch.\n\nDivorced and childless, David\u2019s aspirations are modest. He finds deep pride in providing a reliable, personal service in an increasingly impersonal city. He hopes to modernize the equipment one last time before he retires. Sometimes, on a quiet afternoon, he imagines selling the business and finally traveling, perhaps even visiting Pune to see the city his father left behind. For now, though, he is content being David from Sharma\u2019s Cleaners, a quiet anchor on a bustling San Francisco street."
